defaultThe 
defaultPrimate Society of Great Britain (PSGB) is a UK learned society (Registered Charity No. 290185
default, 
defaulthttp://www.psgb.org/
default) 
defaultaffiliated to the International Primatological Society and the European Federation for Primatology. P
defaultSGB was founded in 1967 to promote research into all aspects of primate biology, conservation and management
default 
defaultwith the publication of the useful results of such research. The 
defaultSociety is very strong scientifically and holds regular scientific meetings. 
defaultPrima
defaultte Eye
default is the PSGB journal, and the Society has also recently adopted 
defaultFolia Primatologica
default as another official PSGB publication. It also awards several medals to mark individual contributions to primatology. PSGB has three permanent working parties: the Cap
defaulttive Care Working Party, the Conservation Working Party, and the Research Working Party.
default1.2.
default 
defaultThe Captive Care Working Party 
default(CCWP) 
defaultconsiders all issues that relate to the use, maintenance and breeding of primates in captivity. It 
defaultprovides expert advice to inte
defaultrested parties within and outside the Society and co-ordinates action on matters relating to the welfare of primates in 
defaultall
default captive settings.
default CCWP also awards grants to support research that benefits primate welfare in captivity, and to assist education pr
defaultojects about captive primate welfare. 
defaultMembership of the CCWP 
defaultincludes
default 
defaultthose
default with specialist knowledge of,
default or a professional interest in, the care of primates in captivity. Currently, membership comprises both researchers and animal welfare representatives who have experience with a range of primate species (
defaultXXX
defaultStrepsirhines
default, New World monkeys, Old Worl
defaultd monkeys, and apes) in a variety of captive settings. One of the challenges facing the CCWP is to form stronger links between all institutions housing primates, particularly research faci
defaultlities, zoos and rescue centres.
default1.3.
default 
defaultPSGB feels that this inquiry is tim
defaultely and that the three areas for focus for the inquiry are vitally important to determining the extent of primate pet ownership, the effectiveness of regulation and the crucial issue of whether primates should be kept as pets at all.
defaultPSGB is 
defaultunable
default to comment with authority on this issue however RSPCA figures from 2009 
defaultindicate there are between 2500-7500 primates kept by private individuals in Great Britain
default.
defaultPSGB submitted a comprehensive review of the Draft Code of Practice on the Welfare of Privately Kept Non-human Prima
defaulttes as part of the Animal Welfare Policy Team Consultation in April 2010. As we are opposed to the keeping of primates as pets
default,
default as detailed below
default,
default we do not believe that the Code of Practice or existing regulatory framework can adequately ensure the necess
defaultary conditions exist
default to make pet ownership acceptable. Other organisations, such as the RSPCA, with more experience of the implementation of regulation are better placed to provide evidence in this area.
defaultThe first part of this is the major area where PSGB can express an authoritative opinion and 
defaultit is the 
defaultmajor 
defaultfocus
default of our submission detailed below. The implementation of a ban would necessarily involve m
defaulticrochipping and registration of all pet primates. They would also all need to be removed from private ownership and placed in 
defaultapproved, licenced facilities where adequate care can be provided
default for the rest of their natural lives or until their quality of l
defaultife is judged to be sufficiently threatened as to require humane euthanasia
default.
